T1  - Neutralizing Job Stressors: Political Skill as an Antidote to the Dysfunctional Consequences of Role Conflict
AU  - Perrewé, Pamela L.
AU  - Zellars, Kelly L.
AU  - Ferris, Gerald R.
AU  - Rossi, Ana Maria
AU  - Kacmar, Charles J.
AU  - Ralston, David A.
Y1  - 2004/02/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159566
DO  - 10.5465/20159566
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 141
EP  - 152
VL  - 47
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examined the neutralizing effects of political skill on relationships between perceived role conflict and strain. Strain was measured as psychological anxiety, somatic complaints, and physiological strain (heart rate and systolic and diastolic blood pressure). Results support the moderating effects of political skill: greater political skill reduced the negative effects of role conflict on all types of strain.
AB  - We examined the neutralizing effects of political skill on relationships between perceived role conflict and strain. Strain was measured as psychological anxiety, somatic complaints, and physiological strain (heart rate and systolic and diastolic blood pressure). Results support the moderating effects of political skill: greater political skill reduced the negative effects of role conflict on all types of strain.
