TY  - JOUR
T1  - Variable Organizational Risk Preferences: Tests of the March-Shapira Model
AU  - Miller, Kent D.
AU  - Chen, Wei-Ru
Y1  - 2004/02/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159563
DO  - 10.5465/20159563
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 105
EP  - 115
VL  - 47
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - March and Shapira's (1987, 1992) model of managers' risk preferences allows for shifts in attention between survival and aspiration levels. Our study provides initial empirical tests of their model using organizational data. We found that the variables affecting risk and the sizes (but not the signs) of these effects differed across performance categories. Organizations performing poorly showed increased risk as they neared bankruptcy. Other firms showed lower risk as performance improved relative to aspirations.
AB  - March and Shapira's (1987, 1992) model of managers' risk preferences allows for shifts in attention between survival and aspiration levels. Our study provides initial empirical tests of their model using organizational data. We found that the variables affecting risk and the sizes (but not the signs) of these effects differed across performance categories. Organizations performing poorly showed increased risk as they neared bankruptcy. Other firms showed lower risk as performance improved relative to aspirations.
